### 3. Impulse Response Functions

The structural VAR uses recursive (Cholesky) identification with EPU ordered first, meaning EPU shocks can affect all variables contemporaneously while no other shock affects EPU on impact.

![IRF PAYEMS](output/irf_payems.png)

**Figure note (Figure 1):** Impulse response function of month-on-month employment growth (PAYEMS) to a one-unit structural shock to the EPU index, estimated from the recursive VAR(1) with EPU ordered first. The solid black line shows the point estimate; the dashed red lines show the 95% bootstrap confidence bands (100 bootstrap replications). The horizontal axis shows months after the shock (0 to 24); the vertical axis shows the response in percentage points. The model is estimated on 1985M2–2019M12.

![IRF INDPRO](output/irf_indpro.png)

**Figure note (Figure 2):** Impulse response function of month-on-month industrial production growth (INDPRO) to a one-unit structural shock to the EPU index. Same specification as Figure 1.

**INDPRO response:** An EPU shock causes an immediate negative response in industrial production growth. The effect troughs around month 3–4 at approximately −0.05 percentage points and is statistically significant (both confidence bands remain below zero) from months 2–10. The effect gradually dissipates and returns to zero by around month 20.

**PAYEMS response:** Employment growth also responds negatively to an EPU shock, but the response is slower and more persistent. The effect troughs around month 4–5 at approximately −0.013 percentage points. The negative effect is statistically significant from months 2–12. Employment returns to its baseline more slowly than industrial production, consistent with firms being reluctant to hire under uncertainty.

**Interpretation:** Higher economic policy uncertainty depresses both real activity variables. Industrial production reacts faster — firms cut output quickly — while employment adjusts more slowly, reflecting the higher costs of hiring and firing.

